instance virtual_to_physical_interaction : DTDFVocab:VirtualToPhysical [
    base:desc "The controller, implemented on the Raspberry Pi, receives temperature measurements from the DT via RabbitMQ and executes a bang‑bang control strategy. When the measured temperature falls below the lower limit (LL) or rises above the upper limit (UL), the controller publishes a command message to RabbitMQ. The low‑level driver consumes these command messages, validates them against the safe‑protocol, and translates them into GPIO signals that drive MOSFETs (isolated by optocouplers) to switch the heatbed and fan on or off. The driver also publishes the current actuator state back to RabbitMQ so that the DT can monitor the physical state. Command execution confirmation is implicit in the state‑update messages; no explicit ACK mechanism is described."
]

instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The DT system is orchestrated around an asynchronous message broker (RabbitMQ) that decouples the physical twin (PT) components – a Raspberry Pi‑based controller and a low‑level driver – from the digital twin services. The controller consumes temperature readings published by the low‑level driver, executes a bang‑bang control loop, and publishes control commands back to RabbitMQ. Digital twin services subscribe to the same message stream: a Kalman‑filter module estimates the unmeasured heat‑bed temperature, a co‑simulation engine performs what‑if analyses using the calibrated Model B, and a self‑adaptation loop monitors anomalies, schedules experiments, recalibrates the model, and re‑configures the controller. All services run as independent processes (or containers) on the same host or distributed across the network, sharing a time‑series database for real‑time visualization. This event‑driven, message‑centric architecture enables modular scaling and clear separation of responsibilities between the PT and DT layers."
]

instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "The incubator Digital Twin follows a multi‑phase lifecycle that mirrors the classic CPS development cycle. 1) **Physical Twin (PT) construction** – the insulated styrofoam box, heatbed, fan, Raspberry Pi controller, DS18S20 temperature sensors, MOSFET driver board and optocouplers are assembled and wired (see Fig. 3‑5). 2) **Model development** – two lumped‑parameter thermal models are derived; Model A uses two free parameters, Model B uses four, capturing the heatbed’s thermal inertia. 3) **Calibration** – controlled experiments are run and the parameters of Model B are tuned using a calibration algorithm that minimizes the error between measured and simulated temperatures. 4) **Digital Twin deployment** – a RabbitMQ message broker (AMQP 0‑9‑1) runs on the Pi, the low‑level driver publishes sensor data and receives actuator commands, the controller implements a bang‑bang logic with H, C, LL, UL parameters, and the DT streams data to a time‑series database for real‑time dashboards. 5) **Runtime monitoring & adaptation** – a Kalman filter estimates the unmeasured heatbed temperature and flags anomalies; a self‑adaptation loop schedules experiments, re‑calibrates Model B, re‑configures the Kalman filter and controller, and runs what‑if co‑simulations to optimise controller settings. 6) **Evolution & governance** – all code and model artefacts are versioned in a public GitHub repository (https://github.com/INTO‑CPS‑Association/example‑incubator), enabling traceability, peer review and incremental updates.  Transitions between phases are managed by the calibration and adaptation algorithms, which replace model parameters and controller settings while preserving the PT‑DT coupling."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "Calibration experiments were performed using the optimized sensor setup (Fig. 11) to generate a data trajectory. Model parameters were estimated (see Document 5) and the resulting models were validated by comparing simulated temperature profiles to measured data (Figure 13). Model B demonstrated a better fit for the heat‑bed inertia compared to Model A. The calibration process and validation results are documented, and the calibrated parameters are used to update the DT models. No explicit confidence intervals or residual‑based re‑calibration procedures are described in the documents."
]

instance dt_technical_connection : DTDFVocab:TechnicalConnection [
    base:desc "The DT’s communication backbone is a single‑node RabbitMQ broker running on the same Raspberry Pi 4 B that hosts the controller and low‑level driver. Components communicate over the local network using the AMQP protocol. The broker is configured for lightweight, in‑memory queues suitable for the low‑latency requirements of the incubator control loop. No external network interfaces are used; all traffic stays within the local network segment. The documents do not specify bandwidth, latency, redundancy, or security mechanisms; the broker is assumed to be unsecured and non‑persistent, relying on the reliability of the Pi’s local storage."
]

instance dt_hosting_deployment : DTDFVocab:Deployment [
    base:desc "The entire DT stack is deployed on a single Raspberry Pi 4 Model B. The Pi runs the RabbitMQ broker, the low‑level driver, and the controller logic. Sensor polling, message routing, and simple control logic are performed locally, eliminating the need for external cloud services. The deployment is on‑premise, edge‑based, and self‑contained. Scalability is limited to the Pi’s resources; for larger deployments, additional Pi nodes or a clustered RabbitMQ setup would be required, but such extensions are not described in the documents."
]

